author: @ashrafshaikh9392
text: 00:00 üõ† This video is the final installment in a beginner Tableau tutorial series, focusing on a complete project. 00:46 üé® The project aims to cover basics but offers insights into various visualizations and data analysis techniques. 01:56 üìä The project uses an Airbnb dataset, specifically the Seattle Airbnb open dataset, with listings, pricing, and reviews. 02:53 üìà The data has been consolidated into one CSV file and made available on GitHub for ease of access. 04:29 üí° Understanding the data columns is crucial as not all data may be relevant for visualization. 06:04 üß© Proper understanding of data relationships is essential for accurate data joining and analysis. 07:15 üîç Data manipulation, such as filtering and joining, ensures accurate visualization creation. 10:50 üîÑ Checking and confirming joins is vital to ensure correct data integration. 12:30 üìâ Removing unnecessary data helps optimize visualization creation and processing speed. 15:44 üè° The project's use case involves optimizing Airbnb listings based on factors like location and pricing. 17:58 üé® Creating visualizations, such as price by zip code, helps identify optimal locations for Airbnb listings. 18:39 üó∫ Maps can be created using location data like latitude and longitude to visualize distribution and patterns. 19:20 üîç When working with zip code data in Tableau, ensure consistency and separate zip codes for better visualization. 21:13 üé® Visualizations in Tableau can be enhanced by adding labels and average price information for better understanding. 23:20 üè° Analyzing the best times for Airbnb listings can be done using time series data in Tableau to identify peak periods of demand. 32:52 üí∞ The number of bedrooms significantly impacts Airbnb prices, with larger homes commanding higher prices per night. 35:40 üìä Visualizing competition for Airbnb listings by the number of bedrooms can provide insights into market demand and competition. 40:17 üìä Completing the dashboard layout in Tableau by arranging visualizations and discussing its potential for answering questions and generating further inquiries. 41:54 üíª Sharing the Tableau dashboard to Tableau Public for easy access and viewing by others, encouraging viewers to explore the provided link for personal use or comparison. 43:07 üìà Encouraging viewers to utilize the Kaggle data for additional fields and explore different data points to create unique dashboards and visualizations for their portfolios.

text: The reason the initial joins failed is because you only joined the review table on id = id and didn't also join the review dates, so every review per location was added to every date, rather than a 1:1 relationship.  The join was bad.
